4. Detailed Implementation Phases
Phase 1: Infrastructure & Data Modeling
Establish the foundational structure, tooling, and database schemas.
Monorepo Initialization: Configure Turborepo for workspace management, shared linting, and build pipelines.
Database & ORM Setup: * Initialize PostgreSQL container.
Define Drizzle ORM schemas in the packages/database module.
Create tables for Organizations, Users, API_Keys, Schema_Registries, and Credential_Records (utilizing JSONB for flexible VC metadata).
KMS Integration: Deploy OpenBao via Docker Compose. Establish the transit secrets engine and write setup scripts to initialize development keys.
Phase 2: Identity, Access, & Multi-Tenancy
Implement the authorization boundaries using better-auth.
Organization Management: Configure the better-auth Organization plugin to support multi-tenancy. Define Roles (Admin, Issuer, Verifier) and Permissions.
Dashboard AuthN: Implement standard OIDC/OAuth login flows for enterprise users accessing the web platform.
SDK AuthZ: Develop API Key generation and validation logic for external developers consuming the Fastify gateway.
Phase 3: Cryptographic gRPC Engine (Rust)
Isolate CPU-intensive cryptographic operations into a highly scalable Rust microservice.
Protocol Buffer Definition: Create .proto contracts defining RPC calls such as SignCredential, VerifyPresentation, and DeriveProof.
OpenBao Client: Integrate vault.rs (compatible with OpenBao) to securely retrieve and utilize private keys for signing operations without exposing them to the API gateway.
VC 2.0 Primitives: Implement core cryptographic suites:
Standard Ed25519Signature2020 for foundational testing.
SD-JWT implementations for Selective Disclosure capabilities.
(Future) BBS+ signatures for advanced Zero-Knowledge Proofs.
Phase 4: High-Performance API Gateway (Bun)
Build the core business logic layer and routing.
DID Resolver Middleware: Implement a routing interface for Decentralized Identifiers.
Initial support: did:key (offline) and did:web (HTTP-based).
Adapter pattern established for future enterprise ledger anchoring (e.g., did:cord).
Schema Fetcher Pipeline: Build a hybrid caching system that fetches JSON Draft 2020-12 schemas from both local/hosted endpoints and distributed public registries, caching them in PostgreSQL/Memory to optimize verification speed.
Core Issuance/Verification Routes: Develop Fastify endpoints that intake draft credentials, validate against schemas, communicate with the Rust gRPC service for signing, and return fully formed VC 2.0 documents.
Real-time Event Bus: Implement Server-Sent Events (SSE) in Fastify to push lifecycle updates (e.g., "Presentation Verified") to the frontend seamlessly.
Phase 5: Web Platform & SDK Ecosystem
Deliver the user-facing interfaces and developer tools.
Enterprise Dashboard (Next.js): Build schema-driven UI forms using Shadcn UI allowing authorized Organization members to draft schemas, define credential templates, and issue VCs.
Consumer Web Wallet (Next.js): Develop a responsive interface for users to receive VCs, view claims, and generate Verifiable Presentations using Selective Disclosure (choosing exactly which fields to reveal).
TypeScript SDK: Finalize the packages/vc-sdk wrapper, exposing typed methods (import { VcClient } from '@acme/vc-sdk') for external developers to easily interface with the API Gateway.
Phase 6: Productionization & High-Volume Scale
Ensure the system is ready for enterprise load and deployment.
Bitstring Status Lists: Implement VC 2.0 highly scalable revocation mechanisms. Generate and host cryptographically signed bitstrings so verifiers can check revocation status locally without pinging the API for every request.
Deployment Configuration: Configure Docker buildx pipelines to ensure seamless cross-compilation from local Apple Silicon (arm64) environments to production cloud instances (amd64).
Observability: Integrate distributed tracing (OpenTelemetry) across the Bun API Gateway and Rust gRPC service to monitor latency and cryptographic bottlenecks.
